metadata.name: Make-believe #4
metadata.description:
#genuary32nd – Let's meet on this make-believe date, in this make-believe place.
I’m having déjà vu, or is it a memory?

This artwork is originally created for the genuary2023 prompt "Art Deco", using the same core algorithm as Memory Module. Made with fractal math and p5js.

Keyboard controls:
[s] Save the current view in live mode.
[1] to [8] Change resolution, 1.5K to 12K.
[g] Toggle texture.

URL params:
&aspect=[aspect ratio, eg 2]
&res=[resolution multiplier, 0.5-8]

Created by Elsif, 2023.02

metadata.name: Out of window #49
metadata.description:
The work is part of a digital art movement that integrates art, mathematics, and physics in the creation of new works of art.
In my work, I deconstruct materials and investigate the nature of bodies and their components, which has some overlap with experimental particle physics. Particle accelerator experimental devices produce a set of geometric shapes and lines, which I have used in this work. Various exotic particles are created through acceleration, filtering, and collisions. It is often my intention to question relationships between objects and contexts, reality and imagination, and realism and abstraction using imaging and machine learning methods. This project is very close to what I think of as the machine mentality that by imagination is activated as demarcation and categorization critique, it conforms.

Made by, p5.js - CSG.js

metadata.name: Giants #27
metadata.description:
Exploring 3D "space" in 2D, a lone Giant sits isolated, his only company are the moons that orbit him and his rings.

Giants vary in color, size, banding, ring makeup, ring thickness and orientation, moons, and the color of the galaxy glowing behind.

The rings vary in color, made up of anywhere between 3 and 45 subrings.

Each planet has a shader gradient, from one color to black, and a perpendicular tint gradient, from one random color to another.

There can be up to 6 moons orbiting the giant, all their own unique colors.

Press 's' in Live View to save a .png

metadata.name: BLOCK PARTY #164
metadata.description:
A generative algorithm exploring isometric grids and recursive divisions with an emphasis on contrasting colors.

A random rectange division is so simple yet creates vastly different and interesting outputs.

An isometric grid provides a unique perspective to the recursion giving each piece a certain depth and contrast.

When does chaotic randomness become beauty and what interesting patterns may emerge?

Press 's' in live mode to save image. Best viewed after save.

* Original code by Matt Lehoullier with p5.js

metadata.name: CRAYONS #142
metadata.description:
Sometimes we like the feeling of being citizens of the places we visit. Our senses adapt to capture in detail the signs of the environment. It is then when we begin to breathe the color that surrounds us and places us in that unique setting.

This is how this inspired collection is born and grows, the colors that enchant us as children on a sheet of paper and now serve to paint every place we visit.

The 6 color palettes of this collection aim to transport us to all those places.

Paris: Its pastel tones strolling along the Trocadero on the banks of the Seine.

Berlin: How to tell the story with color in the graffiti of the East Side Gallery and the wall.

Mexico: Its flavor is in the rainbow of its embroideries, alebrijes and altars.

Kenya: Sunrises and sunsets that impregnate the retina with the tones of the savannah.

Costa Rica: Pure life, pure green, from gentle to intense Monte Lluvioso.

Colombia: Seas of flowers flood the streets with colors and aromas celebrating the Feria De Las Flores

High-resolution png downloads are available by pressing number keys 1 (3000px), 2 (6000px), or 3 (9000px).

metadata.name: Jubilee #81
metadata.description:
Jubilee is a flow field festival celebrating creation. Ribbons scattered through a space meet one another, overlap, and are generally at the mercy of the forces acting upon them. But collectively, what complex forms can they create?

Canvas size is 1200 x 1600 pixels, in either portrait or landscape.

To change canvas size:

[1] 1200 x 1600 
[2] 2400 x 3200 
[3] 4800 x 6400

[s] will save a png at the chosen resolution.
